Text.Value: All right. Show me what you have.
Oh you're no fun at all, are you?
LIAR!
Inspired. The rush of adrenaline does wonders for my creative process.
I feel nothing once the red mist descends. Only the need to kill again.
Reflective. To kill is a profound act, one that should not be taken lightly.
I feel at peace. Life, death - they are part of nature's cycle.
I wipe down my weapon and move on.
To kill in service of my oath is my duty. I'm proud to do it.
My skills keep me alive - I feel no shame in using them.
Feel? I usually start with the pockets, then move on to any jewellery...
I feel at one with the Weave. It dances at my fingertips, longing to be used again, and again...
Enlightened. One can only learn so much from books...
I take time to reflect. To kill is to understand one's self, for better or worse.
I feel no regret. The choice was mine, be it a blessing or a curse.
I relish holding such power. It's why I paid the price I did.
I feel the presence of the terrible and the divine. Killing brings me closer to my god.
Certainty. If I kill, it is because my god demanded it.
Good answer. To kill is the closest thing to knowing the power of the gods themselves.
If I have to kill, I'd rather it be quick and discreet. Mess is for amateurs and maniacs.
I like to mix it up. Sometimes it's a subtle thing, sometimes it's a bloodbath.
I call on the Weave to subdue my enemies. It's effective, though hardly its loftiest application.
Quickly and efficiently. I don't want anyone to suffer.
I'm not buying anything. Now back off.
How will you know my perfect weapon?
I see how you slip-slither closer, belly dragging in the filth. Father is laughing at you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Second time Orin appeared to toy with you. She can't believe you're wasting so much time.

Text.Value: There's a killer inside you, isn't there? It wouldn't take much to push you over the edge.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [DG] Laezel (Orin) transforms into her true form.
[LOGAN] The Smith convulses and jerks, tranforming back into the Orin's form. Can modify the *REUSE* of Orin's transformation in other scenes
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The smith's body jerks and convulses as he transforms into Orin the Red. She smirks. Long transform.

Text.Value: Slowly and painfully. I like to see the fear in their eyes.
I like to hum a little funeral dirge. Add a sense of occasion.
Crush skulls, break bones, snap tendons. I don't kill. I DESTROY.
With a prayer, that they may pass from this life in peace.
I kill without cruelty or malice. Only to preserve the natural order.
I'm not fussy, so long as they die.
Swiftly and without hesitation. So long as I follow my oath, my actions are justified.
I kill quietly and with precision. My prey never sees me coming.
Quickly and quietly. I'm gone before they notice the knife in their back.
I unleash a flood of magic on my enemies. Then I watch them drown.
I prepare carefully, and exploit weaknesses. My knowledge is their downfall.
I find the ki within my opponent. Then I extinguish it.
I kill how I please, and as I please. My weapon answers to no one else.
I call on my patron. Together we obliterate those who oppose us.
With a dedication, that my god will revel in the sacrifice I offer.
I wield my faith as my god demands. Without hesitation or doubt.
Go on. Tell me how you kill.
And when you kill someone, what do you feel?
Do you think you could turn your weapon on those closest to you?
Come - we're all friends here. No need to pretend you don't like to twist the knife.
I know what you do to your allies - smiling as the blade slips between the bones, lip-licking as the insides tumble out.
I like to make them bleed. To sever arteries, tear flesh, to make them scream.
It flows through me as raw inspiration, I never know what my next kill will look like.
I see. Playing to your strengths. Keeping things simple.
When you find the lordling, tell him Orin is watching.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Orin twists her ring and disappears.
EditorData.NodeContext: Playful, menacing. Trying to make player uneasy - she could be hiding anywhere.

Text.Value: That is why you make for such delightful company.
Gortash knows you are coming. Knows you have the Bone Lord's stone. Do not let him hiss hot air into your worm-weakened brain.

EditorData.NodeContext: Acting like she's helping you, but just trying to freak you out. 'Bone Lord's stone' is Ketheric's netherstone

Text.Value: I can see it in your eyes, though - you can't help feeling a tingle of pleasure all the same.
One more question, if you'll humour me.
Let's get to know each other a little better. Perhaps I can make you a customer yet.
So, answer me honestly. Could you kill one you loved?
I'm not buying anything. Now back off.
I feel right. I don't kill anyone who doesn't deserve it.
Bold. Brave, even - if the kill is just.
Do not worry, slaughter kin. My blades are still sharp and sweet. They will greet you soon enough.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Orin twists her ring and disappears.
EditorData.NodeContext: Mocking reassurance - trying to make the player uneasy.

Text.Value: Alive. Nothing like taking a life to make you appreciate your own delicate existence.
Relieved, usually. It's kill or be killed, and I intend to survive.
Call it professional curiosity. Now tell me - how does killing make you feel?
Yes, I seem to have it all. Clubs, swords, maces, bows. Cutting and gutting galore.
I don't see what this has to do with me buying a weapon from you.
My targets earn their deaths. If I slay you, you were no ally of mine.
Without hesitation.
Weak and soft and broken. Oh, sweet sibling, the world has dulled you. Or maybe I poked your mind matter too sharply.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mocking - the player said they would never kill a friend, which Orin finds pathetic. Allusion to the fact she put the tadpole in their skull.

Text.Value: I could end it now - but I'll be patient. Father will see us together again. He will see you bleed.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Orin twists her ring and disappears.
EditorData.NodeContext: Toying with the player, trying to make them uneasy, establish her power over them. 'Father' is Bhaal.

Text.Value: No thanks. I've got everything I need.
Why don't we see if we can find the perfect weapon for you?
It is a pleasure, isn't it? Warm and sweet and sticky.
Powerful, but responsible. To take a life is a grave matter, whether with good or ill intent.
I feel alive.
Powerful. Untouchable. Unstoppable.
You had Father's offer. His glory was in reach, and you cowered like a babe.
You deny yourself the sweetest pleasures. But that can change, given the right circumstances.
I've had enough. I'll buy my weapons elsewhere.
I'm not buying anything. Now back off.
I provide a personalised service for my customers. To make sure the weapon I choose is the perfect fit.
Oh, good answer. Killing is so much more satisfying when you really mean it.
You can't stop yourself any more than stop your blood pumping. You delay the inevitable.
Look at it, come crawling home, hands stained with the Bone Lord's soot. And you carry his stone.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'It' is the Dark Urge player. 'Home' at this point is just the city, not yet the temple. 'Bone Lord's soot' refers to the player having killed Ketheric (his god Myrkul is the Lord of Bones)

Text.Value: You deny yourself, but it won't last. It's in your blood.

EditorData.NodeContext: Menacing/amused by your refusal. Thinks you're weak for resisting your nature.

Text.Value: My weapons are a bargain at any price.
Why do you need to know this?
Wonderful. But, patience is a virtue.
Such imagery. You are an artist with a weapon in your hand, I can tell.
Could I? I already have.
No doubt you came here to choose from my fine selection of weapons?
You could kill him. Let him close and make him feel the tickle of your blade between his ribs.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player previously said they would kill friend. Orin encouraging this thought - playful.

Text.Value: So you string your mewlings along with falsehoods. Such sweet, bloody betrayal you offer them.
You'll do so much worse, by the time I'm done with you.

EditorData.NodeContext: With a smile, ominous - picturing the horrors she'll inflict on you

Text.Value: I've been watching. Waiting. Seeing how you lead your lambs skip-skipping to the slaughter.

EditorData.NodeContext: Toying with the player, thinks they're wasting time indulging their companions. Player previously said they could kill a friend.

Text.Value: Welcome, adventurer! I take it you're new to Rivington.
Marvellous. You treat your friends as a butcher leading cattle to the slaughter.
I'm not sure. Something is missing. A hole that only a blade can fill, perhaps.
So long as it comes with a very generous discount.
Have you come beg-begging, sniffing for our stones? Gortash won't like that. A throat his black hand can't choke the spit from.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mocking, finds your plan ridiculous but enjoys the chaos it will cause. 'Stones' are the netherstones. 'Black hand' reference to the 'Black Hand of Bane', Gortash's god.

Text.Value: Alliances change and change and change again. Friend today, dead tomorrow.
Tell me, how do you like to kill?
He'll find your weaknesses. Stick a knife in the cracks and prise you apart. Unless you get him first.

EditorData.NodeContext: Player previously said they wouldn't kill friend. Orin thinks them pathetic, but is amused at the thought of you trying to take on Gortash.

Text.Value: With a lot of heat and a little panache.
Fast, heavy, and hard.
Depends who I'm killing, and how much they've pissed me off.
Remember - his throat spits lies, but my blade carves the truth. You will read it on your skin soon enough.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Orin twists her ring and disappears.
EditorData.NodeContext: toying with the player, knows the 'truth' about them and is enjoying holding this against them

Text.Value: So you're the lickspittle who crushed the Bone Lord's thrall.

EditorData.NodeContext: First time Orin meets player. 'Bone Lord's thrall' is Ketheric, who player previously killed. Curious.

Text.Value: Hardly a course of action to relish. But were the straits dire enough... perhaps.
A... necessary evil, perhaps, if circumstances are dire enough.
Perhaps. If there was no other option.
You take comfort in knowing your foes deserve their fate? It must be wonderful, indulging in such righteous slaughter.
Fear is the best part, isn't it? To see them realise their life is over, its final moments nothing but agony.
You make killing sound quite dull. Where's the passion?
I feel nothing. It's like I'm not even present.
Sated, as if my parched throat has been fully quenched.
Oh, it's all part of the service. Everybody answers.
I do all I can to keep my loved ones safe from my blade.
What difference does that make?
Killing holds no fear for you, does it? You understand what it takes, and what it gives.
Bold of you to assume anyone is that close to me.
LIAR!
Still rolling in the muck, I see.
Seems you've been paying more attention to my techniques than I realised. I am flattered.
Really? That detachment must be so liberating. Who knows what you're capable of?
To pierce a heart I hold dear? I can hardly bear the thought.
My friends? Absolutely not. Not ever.
I would never kill someone I cared about.
This weapon must be fit for every kill. Even the ones you never think will come.
With maximum carnage. Killing is a duty. But spilling blood is a thrill.
Then you know how beautiful betrayal tastes on the tongue. Delicious.
A deep sadness. I take no enjoyment in it.
I feel the most intense pleasure. Arousal, even.
Exhilarated beyond compare. It is my purpose.

Synopsis:
Gyldro Angleiron the Smith, a crusty human male, runs his smithy in the center of Rivington called Angleiron Smithy.

He usually greets potential customers in front of his smithy. But today, Orin the Red, perverse and malicious, has assumed his likeness and identity to greet the unsuspecting players.

This is her way of learning about the players in person, to tailor-made a death just for them.
